column168: Description Of Events

MATERIAL WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING IN THE MEMPHIS HUB DURING THE UNLOADING OF THE HAZARDOUS CONTAINER.  THE BOX HAD CORROSIVE LABELS ON THE TOP AND BOTTOM OF THE BOX.  THE BOX HAD NO ORIENTATION LABELS OR THIS END UP MARKINGS.  THERE WAS NO PROPER SHIPPING NAME OR UN NUMBER ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE BOX.  THE PROPER SHIPPING NAME FOR THE MATERIAL WAS LISTED AS WASTE SULFURIC ACID.  FEDERAL EXPRESS DOES NOT TRANSPORT HAZARDOUS WASTE.  THE INNER PACKAGING CONSISTED OF STYROFOAM CHIPS SURROUNDING PLASTIC BOTTLES. THE BOTTLES WERE PLACED IN THE BOX OPPOSITE THE LABELS SO THAT THEY MAY HAVE BEEN TRANSPORTED ON THEIR SIDE.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND THE SHIPPER NOTIFIED.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: SHIPPING PALLET COLLAPSED, ALLOWING BATTERIES TO OVER TURN--RELEASING THE CONTENTS OF ONE BATTERY; THE OTHER, REMAINING INTACT, WHILE BOTH STAYED BANDED TO THE PALLET ITSELF.  THE BATTERIES BROKE ON SIDE OF THE PALLET CAUSING THE PALLET TO COLLAPSE AND BATTERIES TO OVERTURN. WE CONTAINED THE SPILL WITH OIL DRY SPILL ABSORBENT POURED DIRECTLY ON THE LIQUID WHILE THE TRUCK WAS PARKED IN THE TRAILER CONTAINMENT SHED.  SPILL WAS CONTAINED INSIDE THE TRUCK.  NO MATERIALS LEAKED OUTSIDE OF THE TRUCK; NONE ON THE GROUND OR INTO ANY WATER SUPPLY. TO REDUCE THE POSSIBILITY OF LEAKAGE OUTSIDE OF THE TRUCK, WE WILL PLACE PLASTIC LINERS UNDER BATTERY PALLETS AND INSPECT EACH CONTAINER ON THE PALLET BEFORE TRANSPORTING.

column168: PACKAGES WERE INSPECTED DUE TO SMALL LEAK. DRIVER NOTICED SEEPAGE OUT OF TRAILER APX 7:30 P.M. IN NEEDLES, CALIF. MADE CALL TO SAFETY PERSONNEL AND IN TURN SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED.  SHIPPER CONTACTED I.T. CORP. OUT OF WILMINGTON CALIF. TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL.  LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THE POLICE WERE MADE AWARE OF THE SITUATION.  CLEAN UP WAS COMPLETED AND ALL EQUIPMENT AND SITUATION WAS INSPECTED BY CHP BEFORE LOAD AND EQUIPMENT WERE ALLOWED TO PROCEED TO DESTINATION.

SWITCHING CREW AT RIGBY YARD REPORTED ODOR OF CHLORINE.  A.E. FREEMAN SAFETY MANAGER RESPONDED AND ON INVESTIGATION FOUND PROX 89190 WITH ANGLE VALVE ON VAPOR LINE TO BE SLIGHTLY LOOSE.  AFTER VALVE WAS TIGHTENED HISS STOPPED AND SMELL SUBSIDED.

RCRX 1104 DISCOVERED LEAKING FROM SAFETY VENT. AT THIS TIME, RAILROAD EMPLOYEE, WHO WAS WORKING IN VICINITY, COMPLAINED OF DIFFICULTY IN BREATHING.  HE WAS TAKEN TO CRAWFORD W. LONG HOSPITAL, ATLANTA, GA, WHERE HE WAS EXAMINED, X-RAYED AND RELEASED. CAR ISOLATED AND SHIPPER NOTIFIED.  SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE RESPONDED AND TIGHTENED BOLTS ON TOP OF SAFETY VENT.  THE FRANGIBLE DISC WAS INTACT. THE FRANGIBLE DISC WAS REPLACED ON ABOVE CAR AT CHATTANOOGA, TN, DECEMBER 30, 1990, AFTER SAME WAS REPORTED LEAKING.  FILE 90-133, 12/31/90, COVERS.
THIS SHIPMENT SHOULD NOT HAVE BEEN DOUBLE STACKED.  2 PLTS WEIGHING 4000 LBS WERE DOUBLED UP.

AFTER HE WOKE UP, HE DID A WALK AROUND THE TRAILER AND NOTICED ABOUT 2" DIAMETER SPILL ON THE GROUND.  THE TRAILER WAS RETURNED TO OUR YARD AFTER THE DRIVER TEMPORARILY FIXED THE EXTERNAL VALVE.  THE SPILLED ALCOHOL EVAPORATED VERY QUICKLY SO NO CLEAN-UP WAS POSSIBLE.

THIS DELIVERY SITE HAD A TANK CHANGE.  THE FILL THAT THE DRIVER HOOKED HIS HOSE TO WAS MARKED 14,000 GAL., THE DRIVER FOLLOWED THE PIPE TO AN ABOVE GROUND STORAGE TANK.  HE THEN PROCEEDED TO STOCK THE TANK AND FILL IT, NOT REALIZING THE TANK NEXT TO IT WAS ALSO PIPED INTO THE SYSTEM.  THE SECOND TANK WAS THE 14,000 GALLON TANK. AT TIME OF SPILL, DRIVER SHUT OFF THE PUMP AND CALLED STAR OIL MANAGER FOR INSTRUCTIONS.  THERE WILL NOT BE ANY MORE AFTER HOUR DELIVERIES.  PER STAR OIL MANAGER.

SEALED TOP OF PLASTIC 55 GALLON CONTAINER LEAKING.  ALL DAMAGED MATERIAL PLACED IN RECOVERY DRUM PENDING DISPOSITION.

WHILE UNLOADING A TRAILER, FORKLIFT BLADES PUNCTURED A DRUM.  THE DRUM WAS IN FRONT OF A PALLET BEING PICKED UP BY THE FORKLIFT BLADES AND THE BLADES PROTRUDED THROUGH THE PALLET SPEARING THE DRUM.  THE PUNCTURED DRUM WAS IMMEDIATELY REMOVED FROM THE TRAILER AND TILTED BACK TO PREVENT FURTHER LEAKAGE.  THE LIQUID CONTENTS WHICH SPILLED WERE COVERED WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND SWEPT UP.  THE HOLE IN THE DRUM WAS TAPED.  THE DRUM AND THE ABSORBENT MATERIAL WERE PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM.  THE SALVAGE DRUM IS BEING HELD FOR PICK-UP BY A PERMITTED HAZARDOUS WASTE TRANSPORTER TO AN EPA-AUTHORIZED DISPOSAL FACILITY. THE EMPLOYEE HAD BEEN COUNSELLED ON OPERATION AND SAFETY PROCEDURES.

AFTER THE DRIVER COMPLETED THE DELIVERY HE WAS WINDING UP THE HOSE.  THE ELECTRIC MOTOR WHICH POWERS THE HOSE REEL GOT STUCK IN THE ON POSITION CAUSING THE NOZZLE TO SLAM UP UNDER THE TRUCK AT WHICH TIME IT OPENED UP SPILLING 5 GALLONS ON THE STREET.  THE DRIVER AND OTHER COMPANY EMPLOYEES CLEANED UP THE SPILL.  ALL MATERIAL USED IN THE CLEANUP HAS BEEN RETURNED TO THE A.P. WOODSON COMPANY TERMINAL FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.

WHILE THE DRIVER WAS MAKING A DELIVERY AT 2200 PACIFIC HIGHWAY, HE MOVED SEVERAL PAIL OF THIS FREIGHT AND KNOCKED OVER TWO PAILS WHICH FELL OVER AND THE TOP COVERS CAME OPEN WHICH ALLOWED THE CONTENTS TO SPILL OUT OF THE PAILS AND ON THE TRAILER FLOOR. WE ARE AWAITING A REPLY FROM THE SHIPPER AS TO DISPOSITION. TO AVOID IN THE FUTURE, MORE CARE HAD TO BE TAKEN BY OUR EMPLOYEES WHEN THEY HANDLE HAZARDOUS FREIGHT TO PREVENT DAMAGE AND SPILLS.  TO BE DISPOSED OF IN A PROPER MANNER.

column168: EMPLOYEE UNLOADING TRAILER WITH FORKLIFT.  DRUMS WERE LOADED IN FRONT OF A PALLET.  WHEN HE PUT HIS FORKS UNDER THE PALLET TO LIFT IT HE WENT IN TO FAR AND PUNCTURED THE DRUM.  THE DRUM WAS TURNED ON ITS SIDE TO PREVENT FURTHER LEAKAGE AFTER LOSING APPROX. 25 GALLONS.  THE SPILLAGE WAS CONTAINED AND ABSORBED WITH SPEEDY DRY.  CONTENTS STILL IN DRUM TRANSFERRED TO RECOVERY DRUM AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER.  SPEEDY DRY CONTAMINATED WITH SPILLED SUBSTANCE IS IN 2 DRUMS AT THIS FACILITY AWAITING PROPER DISPOSAL.

1. WHILE PLACING FORK BLADES BENEATH PALLET IN FRONT OF DRUMS, DOCK WORKER DID NOT REALIZE THAT FORKS EXTENDED BEYOND SKID.  FORK BLADES PUNCTURED DRUMS APPROXIMATELY TWO (2) INCHES FROM BOTTOM.  UPON REALIZATION THAT THE ACCIDENT HAD OCCURRED, EMPLOYEES DIRECTED FROM THE SCENE AND THE TRAILER WAS IMMEDIATELY SECURED (DOOR CLOSED AND LOCKED), AND MOVED OUT INTO THE YARD. 2. EMERGENCY RESPONSE WAS SOUGHT FROM AN OUTSIDE FIRM AND THE PROPER AUTHORITIES NOTIFIED. 3. EMPLOYEES WERE RE-INSTRUCTED REGARDING PROPER FORKLIFT OPERATION NEAR AND AROUND DRUMS TO PREVENT REOCCURRENCE.  IN ADDITION, INSTRUCTIONS WERE CONVEYED THAT DUNNAGE MUST BE PLACED BETWEEN SKIDDED FREIGHT AS WELL AS ALONG SIDE.  THIS MESSAGE WAS CONVEYED TO THE ENTIRE SYSTEM. THERE ARE NO HAZARDOUS WASTE MANIFESTS AVAILABLE AT THIS TIME.

ARRIVED AT PLANT AT 7:53 A.M.  READ SAFETY PROCEDURES, PARKED AT UNLOADING FACILITIES.  ONCE SPOTTED, SUITED UP.  CONNECTED HOSE FROM TRAILER TO PUMP; FROM DISCHARGE OF PUMP TO THEIR PRODUCT FILL LINE INTO TANK (RAILCAR) WHICH HAD BEEN RECENTLY INSTALLED AND COMPLETED (AS MAINTENANCE WAS MAKING FINAL COMPLETIONS UPON OUR ARRIVAL).  DRIVER THEN OPENED VALVES ON TRAILER TO PRIME PUMP, AT THAT TIME DRIVER REALIZED THERE MIGHT BE BLOCKAGE.  DRIVER COMMUNICATED WITH JESSEE CAVAZOS (PLANT OPERATOR RECEIVING PRODUCT).  CAVAZOS STATED VALVES WERE OPEN AND READY.  DRIVER STOPPED OPERATIONS AND CALLED FOR MECHANIC.  PABLO GUTIERREZ ADJUSTED CABLE ON TRAILER PRODUCT DISCHARGE VALVE.  DRIVER AGAIN ATTEMPTED TO PRIME THE PUMP.  DRIVER ACHIEVED PRIME AND BEGAN TO PUMP.  DRIVER THEN WENT TO TRACTOR TO ACCELERATE MOTOR WHEN HOSE BURST.  DRIVER THEN SHUT PUMP AND IMMEDIATELY CLOSED VALVES.

THE TRAILER WENT TO THE RIGHT, HIT A GUARD RAIL & BROKE ABOVE THE UPPER COUPLER PLATE.  THE REAR DOME CAP WAS BROKEN OFF WHEN THE TRAILER OVERTURNED.  THE #6 FUEL OIL SPILLED OUT THROUGH THE OPENING.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: OUR DRIVER HOOKED UP TO THE MANIFOLD THAT CONNECTS 3 CRUDE OIL TANKS, AT THE WELL.  HE OPENED THE VALVE ON THE ASSIGNED TANK AND PROCEEDED TO LOAD. UNKNOWN TO HIM, A FAULTY VALVE ON ONE OF THE OTHER TANKS WAS ALSO LETTING OIL THROUGH.  THE DRIVER OVERFILLED HIS TRUCK AND RAN APPROX. 65 GALLONS OF CRUDE OIL OUT THE TOP OF HIS TRAILER ON THE GROUND.  THE DRIVER CLOSED THE MAIN VALVE AND SHUT OFF THE PUMP.  HE THE RADIOED BASE FOR A CLEANUP CREW.  THE DRIVER CONTAINED THE SPILL WITH A SHOVEL AND PAIL UNTIL THE CLEANUP CREW ARRIVED.  THE CREW RECOVERED THE CRUDE OIL WITH BUCKETS AND SORBENT-C.

column168: NOTE THE TANKER WAS EMPTY AT THE TIME OF THIS INCIDENT EXCEPT FOR THE RESIDUE FROM THE LAST LOAD THAT WAS HAULED.  THE LOAD REFERRED TO WAS THE LAST LOAD HAULED IN THE TANK. (PAC1783961) THE OPERATOR OF THE TANKER WHILE ATTEMPTING TO SUCK UP MATERIAL INADVERTANTLY HIT THE PUMP LEVER CAUSING THE RESIDUE FROM THE LAST LOAD TO BE DISCHARGED ON THE GROUND. THE MATERIAL WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP INTO A SPILL PACK.  THE OPERATOR WAS GIVEN A WRITTEN REPRIMAND AND RETRAINED IN THE USE OF THIS EQUIPMENT.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: LEAKAGE WAS DISCOVERED WHEN TRAILER WAS BEING UNLOADED AT THE DOCK. LEAKAGE RESULTED FROM A LEAKING CLOSURE.

IN THE PROCESS OF UNLOADING THE DRIVER PUMPED ONE COMPARTMENT OF #2 FUEL OIL INTO THE WRONG TANK.  THE DRIVER THEN CALLED DISPATCH.  THE DRIVER WAS TOLD TO PUMP THE #2 FUEL OIL BACK INTO THE TRANSPORT AND PUMP THE PRODUCT INTO THE CORRECT TANK.  WHEN THE DRIVER WAS PUMPING THE PRODUCT INTO THE TRANSPORT THE COMPARTMENT RAN OVER SPILLING 415 GALLONS OF #2 FUEL OIL. AT THIS TIME THE DRIVER REPORTED THE SPILL TO DISPATCH.  DISPATCH CALLED THE STATE DUTY OFFICER AND DETERMAN TANK MINNEAPOLIS, MN. TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL.  ALL THE SPILLED PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED ON A CEMENT SLAB.  NO PRODUCT WENT INTO THE GROUND.  THE SPILLED PRODUCT AND CLEAN UP PADS WILL BE TAKEN TO DETERMAN TANK WHERE THE PRODUCT AND PADS WILL BE PUT IN THEIR FUEL BLENDING PROCESS.

column168: WHILE DELIVERING AMMONIA TO A CUSTOMER IN APPLETON, WISCONSIN, THE DRIVER NOTICED A SLIGHT LEAK AT THE BACK OF HIS TANK TRUCK. THE TRUCK WAS TAKEN TO ROCKET SUPPLY IN ROBERTS, ILLINOIS ON 1/7/91 FOR REPAIRS.
TANK TILTED CAUSING MACIURCATE GAUGE READING AND TANK OVERFILLED DURING UNLOADING.  ADJUSTING DELIVERY SCHEDULE TO ALLOW FOR GREATER ULLAGE.

HE WAS ALMOST STOPPED WHEN HE SLIPPED OFF THE EDGE OF THE PAVEMENT AND THE TRUCK AND TRAILER LAYED OVER ON ITS RIGHT SIDE.  WHEN HE GOT OUT OF THE TRUCK HE FLAGGED DOWN A VEHICLE AND REQUESTED HELP.  WHEN FIRE AND POLICE UNITS ARRIVED, THEY DISCOVERED 2 CAPS ON TOP OF THE TRAILER WERE DRIPPING PRODUCT.  THE DRIVER TIGHTENED THE FITTINGS AND STOPPED THE DRIPPING.

THE DRIVER WAS HAVING A HARD TIME SEEING DUE TO THE FOG AND RAN OFF THE ROAD AND TURNED THE TANKER TRUCK OVER. THIS INCIDENT WAS CAUSED BY DRIVER/OPERATOR ERROR.  NO PACKAGE FAILURE WAS INVOLVED.  OUR DRIVER WAS ATTEMPTNG TO PUMP LIQUID CAUSTIC SODA, 50% INTO A STORAGE TANK.  THE TANK TRUCK PUMP WAS WORKING, BUT WAS NOT PUMPING THE LIQUID. (AFTER THE INCIDENT, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE LIQUID WOULD NOT FLOW DUE TO ICE BLOCKING THE CONSIGNEE'S RECEIVING LINE).  THE DRIVER SHUT OFF THE PUMP.  AS HE UNHOOKED THE TANK TRUCK HOSE, PRESSURE IN THE HOSE CAUSED LIQUID CAUSTIC SODA TO SPRAY UP UNDER HIS FACE SHIELD AND BURN HIS LIPS, NOSE AND NECK.  THE DRIVER SHOULD HAVE OPENED THE DRAIN VALVE ON THE HOSE TO RELIEVE PRESSURE BEFORE DISCONNECTING THE HOSE.  THIS ACTION WOULD HAVE PREVENTED THE LIQUID FROM SPRAYING. THE DRIVER WAS FULLY SUITED AT THE TIME WITH: HARD HAT, FACE SHIELD, GOGGLES, EXPOSURE JACKET AND PANTS, GLOVES AND BOOTS.  THE DIRVER WAS TAKEN BY AMBULENCE TO THE HOSPITAL FOR TREATMENT OF HIS LIPS, NOSE AND NECK AND WAS RELEASED. THIE MINIMAL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT SPILLED WAS CLEANED UP BY FORT MEADE PERSONNEL.  RECOMMENDATIONS TO IMPROVE HANDLNG ARE: 1) TO INSTRUCT DRIVERS TO REQUEST CUSTOMER TO CHECK RECEIVING LINES FOR OBSTRUCTION AND, 2) TO INSTRUCT DRIVERS TO OPEN DRAIN VALVE ON HOSE TO RELIEVE PRESSURE BETWEEN DELIVERY TANK AND RECEIVING TANK, BEFORE DISCONNECTING THE DELIVERY HOSE.

column168: DURING THE SORT AT OUR MINNEAPOLIS RAMP OPERATION A PACKAGE WAS IDENTIFIED AS HISSING.  UPON INSPECTION A "DRY SHIPPER" WAS FOUND TO BE INSIDE THE SEALED HARD PLASTIC CONTAINER.  THE DRY SHIPPER STILL APPEARED TO CONTAIN 1 CUP OF LIQUID NITROGEN IN THE BOTTOM OF THE DRY SHIPPER.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELS, OR PAPERWORK TO INDICATE THIS SHIPMENT WAS A DANGEROUS GOODS.  THE OUTER PACKAGE HAD RUBBER SEALS WITH NO MEANS OF VENTILATION WHAT-SO-EVER.  THE REASON FOR THE HISSING WAS THE EXPANSION OF THE LIQUID NITROGEN FROM THE FEEDER FLIGHT INTO MINNEAPOLIS.  THIS PACKAGE COULD HAVE EXPLODED AND WAS EXTREMELY DANGEROUS.  SO CALLED DRY SHIPPERS MIS-INFORM THE USER GROUPS AND SHOULD BE ADDRESSED WITH THE MANUFACTURING GROUPS.

column168: DUE TO THE LARGE AMOUNT OF CRYOGENIC CONTAINERS SHIPPED THROUGH MINNEAPOLIS, OUR RAMP AGENTS ARE VERY FAMILAIR WITH NON-FLAMMABLE GAS SHIPMENTS. THE SHIPMENT WAS NOT AT ROOM TEMPERATURE AND THIS DID MEET THE PACKAGING REQUIREMENTS FOR DECLARING A DRY SHIPPER AS A NON-FLAMMABLE GAS PER ICAO TECHNICAL INSTRUCTIONS 202.

MOORE (CA HIGHWAY PATROL) WHO HAD NOTICED LIQUID AT THE END OF MR. BRADFORD'S TRAILOR.  MR. BRADFORD SHOWED HIS SHIPPING PAPERS TO THE OFFICER AND THEN PROCEEDE TO NEUTRALIZE THE SPILLED MATERIAL WITH SODA ASH AND REMOVE THE CONTAMINANT FROM THE TRAILOR.  MR.  BRADFORD WAS SITED FOR SHIPPING HAZARDOUS MATERIAL IN A PACKAGE NOT ADEQUATE TO PREVENT LEAKAGE. THE LEAKING OCCURRED AROUND THE GASKET OF THE CAP.  GREAT WESTERN HAS SINCE BEEN FINED $1200.   THE FOLLOWING CORRECTIVE ACTIONS WILL BE TAKEN TO RESOLVE THIS PROBLEM;  -CYLINDERS WILL BE CHECKED THOUTOUGHLY PRIOR TO SHIPMENT TO ENSURE THAT THE CYLINDER IS NOT LEAKING AT THE GASKET. -DRIVERS WILL TIGHTEN BUNGS AND REPLACED GASKETS AS NEEDED.  -THE CYLINDER MANUFACTURED IS RESEARCHING POSSIBLE REPLACEMENTS FOR THESE GASKETS.

DRIVER WAS PUMPING OFF FUEL OIL NO. 2 AND THE DISCHARGE HOSE CAME LOOSE FROM THE PUMP.  DRIVER WAS STANDING NEAR THE PUMP AND VALVES, AND IMMEDIATELY SHUT THE SYSTEM OFF. PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED AND CLEAN-UP BEGAN.

PRODUCT WAS UNLOADED FROM CARGO TANK INTO CUSTOMER'S STORAGE TANK BY USE OF AIR PRESSURE.  WHEN CARGO TANK BECAME EMPTY, THE AIR PRESSURE USED TO OFF LOAD PRODUCT SURGED INTO CUSTOMER'S STORAGE TANK CAUSING PRODUCT TO OVERFLOW THROUGH THE STORAGE TANK VENT AND RESULTED IN AN APPROXIMATE 10 GALLON SPILL. ALL PRODUCT WAS CLEAN-UP AND DISPOSED OF PROPERLY BY CUSTOMER EMPLOYEES.

WE CONSIDER THIS TO BE AN ISOLATED INCIDENT SINCE WE USE COATED NAILS TO PREVENT BACK OUT ON OUR PALLETS.

column62: Corrosion - Exterior; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: THE PARCEL WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING AND WAS REMOVED FROM THE BUILDING. VAPORS WERE COMING OUT OF THE BOX.  THE PARCEL WAS INDENTIFIED AS A CORROSIVE LIQUID.  WE USED 75 POUNDS OF SODIUM BICARBONATE TO NEUTRALIZE THE ACID.  ALSO, 20 POUNDS OF SOLUSORB WAS USED TO ABSORB THE LEAKING MATERIAL. ALL OF THE ACID WAS NEUTRALIZED AND ABSORBED INCLUDING THE WET CONTAINER.  THE CAUSE OF THIS INCIDENT WAS LOOSE FITTING CAPS ON THE 4 ONE GALLON CONTAINERS.  THIS COULD HAVE BEEN PREVENTED BY BETTER PACKAGING INSPECTION OF THE PRODUCT.  THE WASTE WAS PH TESTED TO 7 AND WRAPPED IN PLASTIC SEVERAL TIMES, BOXED AND DISPOSED OF IN THE DUMPSTER.

PACKAGE WAS DAMAGED WHILE LOADING.  ONE OF TWO ONE GALLON BOTTLES WAS CRUSHED. THE COMPLETE PACKAGE WAS REPACKAGED AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER. THE DAMAGED CONTENTS WERE DISPOSED OF FOLLOWING HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DISPOSAL PROCEDURE.

THE CONTENTS LEAKED ONTO THE FLOOR, THE CONTENTS ON THE FLOOR WERE MIXED WITH SOLUSORB TO A DRY STATE, THEN PLACED IN A DOUBLE BAGGED & DISPOSED. THE BOX CONTAINING THE BROKEN GLASS CONTAINER WAS DETAINED IN A WELL VENTILATED AREA,  THEN PLACED IN A DOUBLE BAG WITH SOLUSORB AND MIXED THEN DISPOSED.

THE CYLINDER WAS BEING UNLOADED FROM A COMMON CARRIER, MERCHANT'S TRUCK LINES WHEN AN AIRCO EMPLOYEE NOTICED A STRANGE OFOR.  UPON QUESTIONING THE DRIVER, HE HAD STATED THAT HE HAD NOTICED ONE OF THE CYLINDERS LEAKING EARLIER.  IT WAS DETERMINED TO BE A VERY SLOW LEAK OF NITORGEN DIOXIDE AT 450 PPM AND AIR BALANCE. THE AIRCO EMPLOYEE AND DRIVER WERE SENT TO THE HOSPITAL FOR OBSERVATION.  THE CYLINDER WAS EXAMINED AND THE VALVE WAS CLOSED & THE PLUG WAS TIGHTENED WITHIN A FEW MINUTES OF DETECTING THE LEAK.  APPARENTLY VIBRATIONS DURING SHIPMENT CAUSED THE VALVE TO OPEN SLIGHTLY AND THE PLUG WAS NOT TIGHT.  CORRECTIVE ACTION: THE HANDWHEELS ON CYLINDERS CONTAINING TOXIC GASES IN LEVELS ABOVE THE TLV WILL BE TIED DOWN AND THE VALVE PLUGS WILL BE CHECKED BEFORE SHIPPING..

LONG MEASURING STICK LODGED UNDER THE VALVE WHICH PROHIBITED THE VALVE FROM CLOSING COMPLETELY.  THE STICK WAS REMOVED FROM THE TRAILER.

OUR DRIVER WAS CLEARED FOR DELIVERY AT DESTINATION.  HE HOOKED UP THE TRANSFER HOSE AND STARTED TO TRANSFER THE MATERIAL TO STORAGE. A 55 GALLON PLASTIC DRUM WAS BEING TRUCKED WITH A DRUM DOLLY BY CLIFF MAPLES.  THE SHARP TEETH FROM THE FOLLY PUNCTURED THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM. A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID BEGAN TO LEAK FROM THE DRUM.. WE IMMEDIATELY LAID THE DRUM IN ITS SIDE AND PUT ABSORBENT DOWN TO SOAK UP THE SPILL. CONTAINERIZED CHEMICAL DISPOSAL INC. CALLED TO CLEAN UP SPILL. column168: PACKAGE WAS BROUGHT TO PSC AT 8:30 P.M. CARTON BOTTOM WAS SOAKED.  UPON INSPECTION, WE FOUND TWO SMALL BOTTLES WERE LEAKING.  ONE DUE TO A LOOSE CAP AND THE OTHER JUST RUPTURED. THE DAMAGE COULD HAVE BEEN PREVENTED BY FILLING CARTON WITH A SUFFICENT AMOUNT OF INTERNAL CUSHIONING AND INSPECTION OF CAPS BEFORE SHIPPING.  REMAINING MERCHANDISE WAS OVERPACKED AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER.  ORIGIN CUSTOMER SERVICE TO REVIEW PACKAGING, LABELING AND PERFORMANCE TESTING OF PACK WITH SHIPPER.

DAMAGED WAS REBUCKETED, PUT IN PLASTIC AND OVERBOXED.  SENT RTS-DAMAGED.  (THE PACKAGE WAS LEFT IN THE PSC AREA, WHERE THE BOX CAME FROM IS UNKNOWN)

column168: THE ABOVE LISTED RAIL TANK CARS ARRIVED LAUREL, MT AT 10:45 A.M. ON 01/17/91, WITH DIESEL FUEL LEAKING FROM TOP.  TANK CARS WERE TOO FULL AND EXPANSION OF MATERIAL DUE TO WARM WEATHER CAUSED OVERFLOW.  TANK CARS WERE IMMEDIATELY TAKEN TO LOCOMOTIVE SERVICING AREA AND EXCESS PRODUCT PUMPED OUT.  TWO TANK CARS WERE THEN INSPECTED, FOUND TO BE OKAY AND RELEASED ON TO THE DESTINATION.

ON 1/15/91 AT APPROXIMATELY 9:50 PM RANGER VEHICLE ENTERED PORT OF ENTRY AT FT. MORGAN, CO.  A LIQUID WAS OBSERVED LEAKING FROM THE TRAILER. EXAMINATION DETERMINED THAT THE FLUID WAS AN ORM-A PERCHLOROETHYLENE, A SPENT DRY CLEANING FLUID.  THE TRUCK WAS MOVED TO A SAFE AREA.  RIEDEL ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, DENVER, CO. WAS CONTRACTED WITH TO EFFECT CLEAN UP.  THIS WAS ACCOMPLISHED PROMPTLY.  INSPECTION OF DRUMS INDICATED THAT LIDS WERE NOT PROPERLY SEALED.  THE TRAILER HAS BEEN THROUGHLY CLEANED AND READY TO BE PLACED BACK IN SERVICE.

1. DURING OFF LOADING PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE FAILED CAUSING DISCHARGE OF 25 GALLONS OF FERRIC CHLORIDE SOLUTION IN A CONTAINED AREA. 2. TANKER DEPRESSURIZED. 3. SPILLAGE WAS WASHED DOWN WITH WATER. 4. LIQUID WAS PUMPED BACK INTO THE TANKER. 5. CONTAMINATED DIRT AND ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS SHOVELED INTO DRUMS. 6. TANKER BROUGHT INTO SHOP FOR SERVICE WHERE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE WAS REPLACED.

THE DRIVER OF VEHICLE #1 FELT THE LOAD SHIFT.  LOOKED INSIDE TRAILER TO CHECK ON LOAD AND DISCOVERED THE PRODUCT WAS SEEPING OUT OF THE TOP VALVES.  THE DRIVER TOOK TOWELS AND WIPED THE LIQUID OFF THE VALVES. TWO AUTHORITIES FROM TEXACO CHEMICAL WERE CALLED TO THE SCENE TO TIGHTEN THE VALVES AND STATED THAT THE DRUMS WERE OVERFILLED.

column168: DRIVER WAS MAKING A DELIVERY TO CUSTOMER WHEN THE STORAGE TANK STARTED TO OVERFLOW.  DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SHUT THE EMERGENCY VALVE, THEN STARTED TO SCREW DOWN THE GATE VALVE, ABOUT 5 TO 8 GALLONS RAN ONTO THE CONCRETE DRIVE. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND HAZMAT WERE CALLED, THEY PUT OUT SAND, OIL DRY AND PILLOWS TO ABSORB THE SPILLAGE.  CLEAN UP WAS HANDLED TO EVERYONES SATISFACTION.

UNLOADING PRODUCT AT CONSIGNEE'S, HOOKED UP ALL NECESSARY HOSES AND AIR. DRIVER WENT TO CHECK CONSIGNEE'S HOOK UP WHEN HE NOTICED A SMALL LEAK AT THE FITTING.  FITTING BLEW OFF AND SPILLED ABOUT 5 TO 10 GALLONS OF PRODUCT.

OUR TRUCK WAS HEADING NORTH ON HICKORY HILL ROAD AND WAS STRUCK BY A TRAIN HEADING EAST.  THE COLLISION PUNTURED THE TANK ON OUR TRUCK AND FUEL OIL LEAKED ONTO THE GROUND.  PA STATE POLICE, LOCAL POLICE, LOCAL FIRE AND RESCUE PERSONNEL ASSISTED AT THE SCENE.  PA DER PERSONNEL WERE NOTIFIED AND A LOCAL CLEAN-UP ORGANIZATION WAS CALLED IN TO PROPERLY HANDLE THE ENVIRONMENTAL CONSIDERATIONS.

THIS REPORT IS FILED TO THE BEST OF MY KNOWLEDGE AS I WAS NOT INVOLVED IN THE ORIGINAL INCIDENT.

column25: DU PONT E I DE NEMOURS & CO
column168: AT 0742 HOURS, JANUARY 01, 1991, CONRAIL POLICE DEPARTMENT RADIO DESK (PHILA. PA) RECEIVED NOTIFICATION FROM THE CAMDEN, NJ POLICE DEPARTMENT STATING THAT THEY HAVE RECEIVED REPORTS OF AN ODOR COMING FROM THE CONRAIL RAIL YARD IN THE VICINITY OF THE STATE STREET BRIDGE.  RESPONDING PERSONNEL FROM THE CONRAIL POLICE DEPARTMENT AND THE CAMDEN FIRE DEPARTMENT NOTICED AN ODOR FROM TANK CAR UTLX 89309 WHICH DISAPPEARED SHORTLY AFTER THEIR ARRIVAL.  DETERMINATION WAS MADE THAT CAR WAS EITHER NOT THE SOURCE OF ODOR OR THE CAR WAS NO LONGER LEAKING.  SUBSEQUENT INSPECTION OF CAR ON JANUARY 2, 1991, BY CONRAIL MECHANICAL DEPARTMENT SUPERVISOR INDICATED THAT AN ODOR WAS STILL PRESENT ASROUND THE CAR.  CAR WAS ISOLATED AND SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED.  INSPECTION OF TANK CAR BY BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVE INSPECTOR A RICHTER AT 1600 HOURS INDICATED THAT ODOR WAS COMING FROM THE CAR'S SAFETY RELIEF VALVE.  DUPONT EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSO REPONDED TO THE LOCATION OF THE TANK CAR AT 1800 HOURS AND WERE UNABLE TO R THE SAFETY VALVE.  VALVE WAS SECURED WITH PLASTIC TO MINIMIZE ANY ODOR AND CAR REMAINED ISOLATED.  ON JANUARY 03,1991, DUPONT PERSONNEL WERE ABLE TO A PERMANENT REPAIR TO THE SAFETY VALVE WHICH WAS FOUND TO HAVE TWO WORN "O" R CAR WAS CLEARED TO DESTINATION AT 1250 HOURS, JANUARY 03, 1991.

BOXES WERE ON TOP OF PALLET AND BREAKAGE OCCURRED DUE TO BOUNCING FROM NORMAL DRIVING DURING THE COURSE OF HIS DELIVERIES. column168: WHILE UNLOADING AIRCRAFT, LEAKING PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED.  THERE WERE NO LABELS, MARKINGS OR SHIPPERS CERTIFICATION ON THE BOX.  FURTHER INSPECTION INDICATED THE LIQUID TO BE A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL, BASED ON INFORMATION FROM AN ENCLOSED PACKING LIST.  THERE WAS NO EXTERNAL LEAKAGE BEYOND THE BOX, NOR ANY DAMAGE TO THE AIRCRAFT.  SPECIAL AGENT, AL ROCCHIO OF THE FEDERAL AVIATION ADMINISTRATION IN PHILADELPHIA WAS NOTIFIED.  THE PACKAGE WAS CONSIGNED FOR DISPOSAL UPON COMPLETION OF INVESTIGATION BY AGENT ROCCHIO.

DRIVER/SALESMAN CARSON AURAND WAS UNLOADING TRAILER AND WENT TOO FAR INTO THE SKID BEHIND THE DRUM CONTAINING THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL WITH A FORKLIFT.  THE BLADES FROM THE FORKLIFT SUBSEQUENTLY PUNCTURED THE DRUM ABOUT 2" FROM THE BOTTOM IN THE SIDEWALL.  E. & K. HAZARDOUS WASTE SERVICES - SHEBOYGAN, WI WAS CALLED BY CONSOLIDATED FREIGHTWAYS TO HANDLE THE CLEANUP.  THE SHIPPER WAS CALLED FOR INSTRUCTION AND COPIES OF THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEETS.  PROPER USE OF THE FORKLIFT WAS AGAIN STRESSED AND DISCUSSED WITH THE DRIVER/SALESMAN AND DISCIPLINARY ACTION WILL BE TAKEN.

column168: SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIAL (SSA/HM) HARRY RODABOUGH WAS NOTIFIED BY MR. RUSS MAYNE (PLANT MANAGER, CENEX) OF A SPILL IN TRAILER CFKZ 251811.  SSA/HM RODABOUGH'S INSPECTION REVEALED THAT TWO PALLETS HAD MOVED FROM SIDE TO SIDE DURING TRANSPORTATION CAUSING SOME OF THE PACKAGES TO BREAK OPEN.  THE LOADED PALLETS WERE PLASTIC WRAPPED AND CONTAINED MOST OF THE SPILLAGE.  APPROXIMATELY TEN (10) POUNDS OF THE ORGANIC PHOSPHATE HAD SPILLED ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER.  PRODUCT WAS RECLAIMED AND ARRANGEMENTS MADE TO HAVE TRAILER CLEANED AT THE POCATELLO RAMP. CHEMTREC, SHIPPER AND NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER WERE ALL NOTIFIED.

DRIVER WAS UNLOADING AT THE COASTAL-QUINTANA PLANT IN CORPUS CHIRSTI, TEXAS, WHEN ALL OF THE HCL WAS OFF LOADED AND HOSE JUMPED, THE OPERATOR TOLD OUR DRIVERS TO CLOSE OF THE LIQUID LINE AT THE CONNECTION WHERE OUR HOSE WAS CONNECTED TO THEIR LINE AND AIR SUPPLY AT THE SAME TIME.  WE DID THIS AS SOON AS POSSIBLE, BUT IN THE MEANTIME THE VAPOR VENT LINE FROM THEIR TANK THAT GOES TO A PIT CAUSED A CLOUD OF HCL VAPOR.  THIS CLOUD DRIFTED TO WHERE SOME CONTRACT CONSTRUCTION WORKERS WERE.  MR. J. R. DELEON (SAFETY INSPECTOR) TOLD ME SOME OF THESE WORKERS WERE BEING CHECKED OUT TO SEE OF THEY NEEDED TO BE TREATED.  AFTER THE FIRST RELEASE (WHICH CAME FROM THEIR VENT LINE) OUR DRIVER DID OPEN A BLEED LINE FOR A FEW SECONDS, BUT NO OTHER WORKERS WERE AROUND AT THIS TIME.  I TALKED WITH MR. DAVID NATIVIDAD (OPERATOR), MR. PENA AND D. GAY AND ALL AGREE ON THIS STATEMENT: VENT LINE FROM PLANT STORAGE TANK DID NOT VENT TO A PROPER SCRUBBER FOR THIS PRODUCT.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: MR RAYMOND MALDONADO, A GETTY DRIVER, WAS DELIVERING PRODUCT TO THE GETTY STATION AT 1 MONTAUK HIGHWAY IN EAST ISLIP, N.Y. AT 3:45 A.M. ON JANUARY 31, 1991.  THE DRIVER STATED HE HAD FAILED TO TAKE STICK READINGS BEFORE HE STARTED DROPPING THE PRODUCT.  WHILE HE WAS DROPPING THE GASOLINE, THE DRIVER NOTICED GASOLINE RUNNING FROM THE PREMIUM TANK.  HE IMMEDIATELY SHUT DOWN THE VALVE ON THE TRUCK.  HE THEN CALLED AND NOTIFIED OUR LONG ISLAND CITY DISPATCH OFFICE AT APPROXIMATELY 4:00A.M.  MR. DONALD WILLIAMS, A TERMINAL SUPERVISOR, CALLED ME AT HOME AT 4:00A.M.  I TOLD HIM I WOULD CALL HIM RIGHT BACK.  I DID, AND TOLD HIM TO NOTIFY THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT AND ALL OTHERS ON HIS CALL LIST.  I ARRIVED AT THE SCENE AT 5:10 A.M. TO FIND THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT SPREADING SPEEDY DRY ON THE SPILLED PRODUCT.  THE DRIVER HAD PUT A 18" MINI-BOOM BY THE SEWER, WHICH WAS STILL IN PLACE, TO PREVENT ANY PRODUCT FROM ENTERING THE SEWER. MR. ALAN LOEFFLER, WHO IS CHIEF OF THE TOWN OF ISLIP HARBOR POLICE, TOLD ME HE HAD ALREADY SPOKEN TO A MR. JOHN HOFMANN OF THE D.E.C., AND HE GAVE ME A SPILL NUMBER THAT MR. HOFMANN HAD GIVEN HIM (#9011460).  I THEN WENT OVER TO THE DRIVER, WHO I PREVIOUSLY TOLD TO SAY BY THE TRUCK, AND ASKED HIM WHAT HAPPENED.  MR. MALDONADO STATED HE HOOKED UP TO THE REMOTE FILLS AND STARTED TO DROP HIS PRODUCT, WITHOUT CHECKING THE STICK READINGS OR CAPS.  WHEN I ASKED HIM WHY HE SAID HE THOUGHT IT WAS A 10,000 GALLON TANK, NOT AN 8,000 AND THAT IT WOULD FIT IN THE TANK HE WAS PUTTING IT IN. HE ALSO TOLD ME THE HIGH LEVEL ALARM NEVER SOUNDED.  I CHECKED THE TRUCK AND THE DRIVER HAD 1,450 GALLONS OF PRODUCT IN ONE COMPARTMENT AND 550 GALLONS IN THE 2,300 GALLON COMPARTMENT.  HE WAS SUPPOSE TO DELIVER 3,200 GALLONS OF PLUS, 3,750 GALLONS ON UNLEADED REGULAR, AND 5,050 GALLONS OF PREMIUM.  WHEN I CHECKED THE STATIONS INVENTORY FROM THE PREVIOUS MORNINGS, I FOUND THE PLUS GALLONAGE CHECKED OUT WITH 3,200 GALLONS DELIVERED AND SO DID THE 5,050 GALLONS OF UNLEADED REGULAR.  I THEN STUCK FOR WATER, BUT ALL TANKS HAD LESS THAN A HALF INCH OF WATER,  THE PREVIOUS DAYS (1/30/91) INVENTORY SHOWED THE PRODUCT IN THE PREMIUM TANK TO BE 5,694 GALLONS (62"), LESS 181 GALLONS OF GAS PUMPED FOR THE DAY (1/30/91), PLUS 1,750 GALLONS DELIVERED, COMES TO A BALANCE OF 7,263 GALLONS OF INVENTORY.  THE TOTAL CAPACITY OF THIS TANK IS 7,829 GALLONS OF PRODUCT. I FEEL THE PROBABLE CAUSE OF THIS SPILL IS MORE THAN ONE.  FIRST, THE STATION HAD GIVEN THE DISPATCH OFFICE INCORRECT STICK READINGS.  SECOND, THE DRIVER FAILED TO STICK THE TANKS BEFORE DROPPING THE PRODUCT.  THIRD, IF HE HAD STUCK THE TANKS HE WOULD HAVE SEEN NO COVERS WERE ON THE PREMIUM OR UNLEADED REGULAR TANKS.  TO CORRECT THE SITUATION I INSTRUCTED MY DRIVERS THAT, AS ALWAYS, THE DRIVERS ARE RESPONSIBLE TO STICK THE TANKS AND INSURE THE COVERS ARE ON BEFORE DROPPING THE PRODUCT.  I CALLED MAINTENANCE TO HAVE TWO CAPS INSTALLED.

column168: THE DRIVER, RAY HARPER, STATED THAT HE EXAMINED THE LOAD BEFORE ACCEPTING FOR TRANSPORT AND ROUTINELY CHECKED THE LOAD FOR LEAKAGE DURING TRANSPORT. RAY STATED THAT THE LOAD DID NOT LEAK IN ANY WAY UNTIL HE WAS PARKED ON AN INCLINE PRIOR TO CROSSING THE SCALES.  THE STEEP INCLINE ALLOWED A SMALL AMOUNT, LESS THAT 1 PINT, TO DRIP FROM THE ENDGATE ON TO SCALE RAMP.  THE DRIP STOPPED WHEN THE TRUCK WAS MOVED AND PARKED ON LEVEL RAMP.  ABSORBANT WAS PLACED ON THE SPILL SPOT, THEN PICKED UP AND DISPOSED OF WITH THE LOAD.  IT CAN ONLY BE SPECULATED AS TO THE SOURCE OF THE LIQUID (WATER) THAT LEAKED FROM THE LOAD, WHICH CONSISTED OF MAINLY TRASH AND DEBRIS. THE DRIVER STATED THAT THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS NOT ANALYZED TO DETERMINE IF ANY HAZARDOUS CONSTITUENTS WERE PRESENT.  THE GENERATOR, ENSCO, WAS NOTIFIED OF THE SPILL. ENSCO ADVISED ME THAT ADDITIONAL ABSORBANT (FLY ASH) WOULD BE PLACED IN THE FLOOR AND ALONG THE END GATE OF EACH DUMP LOADED WITH DEBRIS OR ANY OTHER MATERIAL IN AN EFFORT TO PREVENT ANY REOCCURRING SPILLS OF THIS TYPE.

column168: CLEAN-UP TRANSPORT'S DRIVER STATED THAT HE ARRIVED AT THE USPCI FACILITY AROUND 11:45 AND HAD TO WAIT IN LINE OUTSIDE THE GATE TILL 1:15 P.M. ON 1-31-91.  AFTER CROSSING THE SCALES HE WAS DIRECTED TO PARK IN THE PARKING AREA PRIOR TO UNLOADING IN THE SOLIDIFICATION BUILDING.  AT 2:15 P.M. USPCI PERSONNEL NOTICED A DRIP FROM THE REAR OF THE END DUMP TRAILER.  THE LEAK WAS TEMPORARILY STOPPED AND THE DRIVER DIRECTED TO PROCEED TO THE SOLIDIFICATION BUILDING WHERE  THE LOAD WAS DUMPED FOR SOLIDIFICATION. USPCI PERSONAL COLLECTED A SAMPLE OF THE LIQUID FROM THE SPILL AND ANALYZED IT TO DETERMINE IF A REPORTABLE QUANTITY HAD BEEN REACHED.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT AN (RQ) WAS MET AND THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER WAS NOTIFIED, REFERENCE REPORT #57468.  APPROXIMATELY 1/4 CUBIC YARD OF SOIL WAS REMOVED AND PLACED WITH THE LOAD FOR PROPER SOLIDIFICATION AND DISPOSAL.  THE MATERIAL TRANSPORTED WAS (RQ) HAZARDOUS WASTE, SOLID, N.O.S., ORM-E NA 9189.  THIS MATERIAL IS ASH FROM THE INCINERATORS OF RCRA HAZARDOUS WASTE AND FREQUENTLY CONTAINS SHARDS OF METAL AND OTHER SHARP OBJECTS. BEFORE LOADING INTO LINED (PACTECH BRAND) END DUMP TRAILERS, FLY ASH OR CEMENT IS MIXED WITH THE MATERIAL, TO ABSORB ANY BRINE CONTAINED IN THE ASH FROM THE INCINERATION STACK SCRUBBER. THE DRIVER STATED THAT HE PULLED THE TARP FORWARD AFTER ENTERING THE FACILITY.  THIS ACTION MUST HAVE DISTURBED THE LINER OR RESULTED IN IT BEING PUNCTURED CAUSING 2 GALLONS OF MATERIAL TO DRIP FROM THE END GATE. I HAVE NOTIFIED THE GENERATOR, ENSCO, ABOUT THIS AND OTHER RECENT INCIDENTS OF THIS TYPE AND STRESSED THE IMPORTANCE OF NOT SHIPPING THE MATERIAL IN A DAMP OR MOIST STATE. CLEAN-UP TRANSPORT DRIVERS HAVE BEEN REMINDED IN THEIR 'DRIVERS WEEKLY NOTICE', THAT IT IS THEIR RESPONSIBILITY TO INSPECT EACH AND EVERY LOAD, REFUSING ANY END DUMP LOADS CONTAINING LIQUIDS OR APPEARING WET.  A PROBLEM WITH THE MATERIAL IS THAT IT APPEARS TO BE DRY AND FREE OF ANY LIQUIDS AT THE TIME OF LOADING, BUT IT MAY SEEP OR LEAK AT THE UN-LOADING DESTINATION,IF ALLOWED TO BE PARKED FOR A PERIOD OF TIME ESPECIALLY ON AN INCLINE.  FLY ASH IS PLACED AT THE END GATE OF EACH TRAILER PRIOR TO LOADING MATERIAL BUT APPARENTLY THE FLY ASH, WHICH HAS THE CONSISTENCY OF FACE POWDER, DISPERSES AWAY FROM THE END GATE DURING TRANSPORT REDUCING THE EFFECTIVENESS OF IT'S PURPOSE. ENSCO'S WASTE HANDLING MANAGER, TERESA EVANS HAD ASSURED ME THAT ENSCO WILL ADD MORE FLY ASH TO THE MATERIALS, AND AT THE REAR OF EACH END DUMP TO REDUCE THE POSSIBILITY OF THIS TYPE INCIDENT OCCURING AGAIN.

column168: RE: INCIDENT 910247 ON JANUARY 19, 1991, OUR DRIVER, DON SHEPPARD, WHILE UNLOADING AT DELTA SONIC IN PALATINE NOTICED THAT SOME GAS HAD COME BACK UP THROUGH THE TANK STICK HOLE.  THIS PRODUCT RAN DOWN APPROXIMATELY 20 FEET OF ASPHALT BEFORE GOING INTO THEIR STORM SEWER.  ACCORDING TO THE PALATINE FIRE DEPT., THE MAJORITY OF THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED WITHIN THE DELTA SONIC STORM SEWER SYSTEM.  RIEDEL ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES CAME TO THE SCENE AND PUMPED OUT THE CATCH BASINS.  THEY RECOVERED FIVE 55 GALLON DRUMS OF LIQUID (60% WATER AND 40% GAS) APPROXIMATELY 100 GALLONS OF UNLEADED GASOLINE AND THREE DRUMS OF OIL DRY.

CYLINDER WAS UNLOADED AT AIRCO'S FACILITY AND ACCORDING TO MERCHANT'S DRIVER, WILLIAM MCKINLEY, THE AIRCO EMPLOYEE DROPPED THE CYLINDER HARD WHEN UNLOADING.  WHEN MY DRIVER GOT DOWN OUT OF BACK OF TRAILER AIRCO EMPLOYEE SAID HE SMELT A STRANGE ODOR AND MY DRIVER AGREED AND THEN THE AIRCO EMPLOYEE SIGNED OUR DELIVERY RECEIPT AND SENT OUR DRIVER ON HIS WAY. ABOUT 10-20 MINUTES AFTER DELIVERY WAS MADE MR. MCLEAN OF AIRCO NOTIFIED US TO HAVE OUR DRIVER RETURNED TO GO TO THE HOSPITAL WITH THEIR EMPLOYEE. OUR DRIVER HAD ALREADY BEEN TO HIS NEXT STOP AND WAS ON HIS WAY BACK IN. MR. MCLEAN TOLD US THIS GAS COULD BE FATAL AND THE EFFECTS WOULD SHOW UP IN 5 TO 8 HOURS. WHEN OUR DRIVER RETURNED WE HAD PARAMEDICS HERE AND OUR DRIVER TOLD THEM HE HAD NO SYMPTOMS AND FELT FINE SO THEY LEFT.  I INSISTED THAT I BRING HIM TO THE HOSPITAL TO HAVE HIM CHECKED OUT WHICH THEY KEPT HIM AND THE AIRCO EMPLOYEE FOR 2 DAYS FOR OBSERVATION. THEY WERE BOTH RELEASED WITH NO APPARENT EFFECTS.  MR.  MCLEAN ALSO TOLD ME THAT THIS CYLINDER SHOULD HAVE HAD A WIRE TIE ON THE VALVE TO MAKE SURE IT COULDN'T TURN TO BE OPENED.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Water Damage
column168: SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) DEAN COOPER WAS NOTIFIED BY THE LAS VEGAS CAR FOREMAN ADVISING TANK CAR 2478 WAS NOTED LEAKING FROM THE TOP DURING SWITCHING OPERATIONS.  SSA/HM COOPER CONTACTED THATCHER CHEMICAL IN HENDERSON, NV AND REQUESTED THEY INSPECT THE CAR TO DETERMINE THE CAUSE OF THE RELEASE.  A THATCHER REPRESENTATIVE INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND THE 100 LB SAFETY VENT RUPTURE DISC WAS BLOWN.  THATCHER REPRESENTATIVE REPLACED THE DISC WITH LIKE DISC AND CAR WAS RELEASED TO MOVEMENT TO THATCHER FOR OFF LOADING.

CARMAN, ELROY MUNSTER, NOTICED RAIX 5033 LEAKING FROM THE TOP DURING SWITCHING OPERATION.  CARMAN MUNSTER NOTIFIED CHEMTREC WHO IN TURN NOTIFIED UNION CARBIDE.  UNION CARBIDE REPRESENTATIVES FROM TEXAS CITY RESPONDED AND REPAIRED THE MANWAY COVER GASKET AND TIGHTENED THE MANWAY BOLTS.  THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR SHIPMENT.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Derailment
column168: TRAIN NLKC2-11 HAD SIXTEEN CARS DERAIL AT INOLA, OKLAHOMA, MP 603 ON VAN BUREN SUBDIVISION.  SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIAL (SSA/HM) C.L. HILL INSPECTED DERAILED CARS AND NOTED VMCX 1059 ON ITS SIDE WITH BOTTOM OUTLET CAP BROKE AWAY DROM THE CAR.  A SMALL MOUNT OF RESIDUE WAS NOTED ON GROUND DIRECTLY BELOW OUTLET.  SSA/HM HILL DETERMINED THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS CRACKED OPEN.  VALVE WAS SECURED AND LEAK STOPPED. CHEMTREC AND SHIPPER WERE NOTIFIED.
